steps.content:
{
  "success": true,
  "data": {
    "query": "battery storage revenue arbitrage day ahead market modeling",
    "num_results": 5,
    "filters_applied": {
      "market": null,
      "data_type": null,
      "year_start": null,
      "year_end": null,
      "range_type": null
    },
    "documents": [
      {
        "id": "02464d85-dfcf-46b6-841c-7dfb520c62c2",
        "score": 0.7071572,
        "text": "This document page discusses the variation in estimated net energy and ancillary services (E&AS) revenues for battery storage systems based on factors such as duration, location, and bidding strategy. The focus is on 2-hour and 4-hour battery storage in Long Island, with revenues modeled under different bidding strategies.\n\nKey points include:\n\n1. **Revenue Modeling Approach**: The battery is assumed to offer its capacity as 10-minute spinning reserves in the day-ahead market and then self-schedules charging or discharging in the real-time market to exploit energy arbitrage and reserve opportunities. If the battery sells day-ahead reserves, it must maintain at least one MWh of charge per MW of reserve sales.\n\n2. **Figure 10**: Shows estimated storage revenues for Long Island from 2022 to 2024, comparing scenarios with 0% and 100% day-ahead reserve sales for 2-hour and 4-hour batteries. Revenues are highest in 2022 and decline in 2023 and 2024. Offering a larger share of capacity as day-ahead reserves results in higher revenues.\n\n3. **Figure 11**: Compares estimated storage E&AS revenues across different locations (NYC, Long Island, North, Jericho Rise WT). Revenues vary by location, with Long Island and NYC showing higher values.\n\n4. **Analysis Findings**:\n   - Revenues were highest in 2022 due to higher and more volatile energy prices.\n   - Selling day-ahead reserves increases revenues despite limiting real-time arbitrage opportunities.\n   - A 4-hour battery earns only about $10 per kW-year more than a 2-hour battery under the highest-revenue strategy (100% day-ahead reserve sales).\n   - Energy market revenues for batteries currently depend heavily on day-ahead reserves.\n\n5. **Implications**: The results suggest that strategies to increase flexibility for real-time energy arbitrage could be beneficial, as current revenues are tied to day-ahead reserve sales.\n\nA footnote clarifies that the battery operator does not have perfect foresight of real-time prices and uses an algorithm based on day-ahead forecasts, real-time market forecasts, and historical prices to decide charging/discharging thresholds.\n\nOverall, the page highlights the importance of bidding strategy and market conditions on battery storage revenues and suggests potential benefits from enhancing real-time market participation flexibility.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/NYISO/report/2024/page_44.jpg",
          "page_num": 44,
          "title": "2024 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2024,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "d0d122cb-2ef1-413e-a3cf-97d1bed9d6db",
        "score": 0.6870037,
        "text": "This page from the appendix of the \"2019 State of the Market Report\" details the methodology and assumptions used for estimating net revenues from battery energy storage resources in the real-time electricity market.\n\nKey points include:\n\n- The hourly charge and discharge offers in the real-time market are calculated as the product of two components: (a) the minimum (for charging) or maximum (for discharging) of forecasted hourly Coordinated Transaction Scheduling (CTS) and Day-Ahead (DA) prices for the rest of the day, and (b) an empirically estimated adjustment factor.\n- The battery storage operator updates forecasts of minimum and maximum prices throughout the day based on (a) price forecasts from the CTS process between ISO-NE and NYISO, which look ahead 150 minutes, and (b) prices from the day-ahead market.\n- Adjustment factors for charge and discharge offers are set monthly to values that maximized profits in the prior month.\n- Assumptions about battery state of charge include that if the battery is not fully charged by hour 15 in winter or hour 4 in summer, it will be fully charged in the subsequent hours regardless of price forecasts. Similarly, the battery is assumed to be fully discharged by hours 19-20 daily.\n- Table 9 summarizes key cost and operating parameters used for net revenue estimates, including:\n  - Investment cost: Mid $851/kW, Low $666/kW (2024 dollars)\n  - Fixed Operations & Maintenance (O&M): Mid $21/kW-year, Low $17/kW-year\n  - Round-trip efficiency: 86%\n  - Project life: 20 years\n  - Property tax: 1.00%\n  - Depreciation schedule: 7-year MACRS\n\nFootnotes clarify that adjustment factors are based on maximizing prior month profits and that cost assumptions derive from NREL\u2019s 2019 Annual Technology Baseline, adjusted for a 2-hour resource and regional cost multipliers for New England.\n\nOverall, this page explains the approach to modeling battery storage market offers and the financial assumptions underlying net revenue calculations.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/ISONE/report/2019/page_81.jpg",
          "page_num": 81,
          "title": "2019 Assessment of the ISO New England Electricity Markets",
          "year": 2019,
          "market": "ISONE",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
